#Delete NA rows within the data set
Newdata<- CAData %>% drop_na()
#Rename the first three columns with their real-world names
Newdata <- rename(Newdata, "AnnualMeanTemperature" = "bio1", "Isothermality" = "bio3" ,"MeanDiurnalRange" = "bio2",)
#Getting rid of unused columns
Newdata<- subset(Newdata, select = -c(grid_cell, bio4, bio5, bio6, bio7, bio8, bio9, bio10, bio11, bio12, bio13, bio14, bio15, bio16, bio17, bio18, bio19, geometry))
#Changing celcius to fahrenheit
Newdata$AnnualMeanTemperature <-(Newdata$AnnualMeanTemperature*1.8+32)

Newdata$MeanDiurnalRange <-(Newdata$MeanDiurnalRange*1.8+32) 

Newdata$Isothermality <-(Newdata$Isothermality*1.8+32)
#Using three mathematical Functions
summary(Newdata)

#First graph
ggplot(data=Newdata, aes(x= AnnualMeanTemperature, y= X_ENDC_RICHNESS_)) + geom_point(color= "red", alpha = .5)

#This graph is comparing species richness to the annual mean temperature.The first part of the code identifies which data set to pull the numbers from, then aes is used to choose the x and y axis for the plot. Next is the geom point line which is used to change the color of the plotted points along with alpha which makes them slightly transparent and easier to see.
#second graph
ggplot(data=Newdata) + geom_line(aes(x=X_ENDC_RICHNESS_, y= Total_Specimens, color = "brown"))

#for this graph I compared the species richness on the x axis and the total number of specimen found for the y axis. After putting ggplot to make the graph, data= is used to show which data set to use. geom_line creates the type of graph. aes is used to choose x and y axis. Then I added color = to change the color of the line to brown.
